#8 Hyperglycemia in the setting of diabetes mellitus
#9 History of hyperlipidemia
#10 History of gastroesophageal reflux disease
#11 History of end-stage renal disease on dialysis
PLAN BY SYSTEMS
1. Neurological:  Continue to follow neurological exam.  Hydromorphone for pain control.  Continue escitalopram.
2. Pulmonary:  Clinically oxygenating and ventilating well.  Encourage good pulmonary toilet.
3. Cardiovascular:  Acceptable hemodynamics.  Intravascularly, she is not in excess.  No signs of cardiac ischemia.  Overall descent perfusion.  It is surprising with her significant coronary artery disease that she is not on a beta-blocker; however, it would appear this has been discontinued because of hypotension.  She is to receive a 3 L fluid pull today, which I think is appropriate.
4. Renal:  Dialysis per Nephrology.  As mentioned earlier, 3 L fluid pull tonight which is appropriate.  Postdialysis labs in the morning.
5. Gastrointestinal:  NPO for this evening.  Advance diet as tolerated with return of bowel function.  Continue intermittent suction on her NG tube.
6. Infectious disease:  No active issues.  She should be receiving periprocedural cefazolin with an appropriate stop date.  She is also on metronidazole.
7. Endocrine:  She is on low-dose prednisone which appears to be a chronic medication for her.  We will continue this.  Continue simvastatin.  She is also covered with insulin.
8. Hematological:  Transfused to keep her hemoglobin above 8 g/dL.  TEDs, SCDs, and subcutaneous heparin in place.  She is also on an aspirin.
9. Access:  She has her dialysis catheter which has been intermittently used for IVs.  I think this is not a great option.  Tonight, she has peripheral access which is poor.  We will place a foot IV, and I think she should get a PICC line, at least while she is hospitalized.
10. Social:  I spoke to the patient, updating her as to the plan of care.

