[start section id="20102"]

We have been asked to see this Ashdown-year-old Caucasian female by Dr. Billy Langley for evaluation and management of cardiopulmonary systems status-post left hemicolectomy and ileosigmoid anastomosis for sigmoid cancer.  The available history including the intraoperative course has been reviewed.
I have seen and evaluated the patient and reviewed the pertinent imaging and laboratory data.  I discussed the patient's care with the critical care house staff as well as nursing.  Please refer to the resident's note of today's date for additional details.

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

Mrs. Duran is an Ashdown-year-old Caucasian female with an abundance of medical problems including depression, restless legs, hypertension, coronary artery disease with a-positive DSE (November 2008 with an ischemic threshold of 109 beats per minute), diastolic heart dysfunction, diabetes mellitus, end-stage renal disease on dialysis who was admitted July 16, 2010, with fevers and chills concerning for healthcare-associated pneumonia.  She was eventually found to have a right segmental pulmonary emboli, splenic infarct, and anemia.  Further workup of her anemia showed a colonic mass in the descending colon.
On August 4, 2010, the patient was taken to the operating room where she underwent a left hemicolectomy and ileosigmoid anastomosis.  From a surgical standpoint, there were no complications.  Anesthetically, the procedure was performed under a general endotracheal anesthetic.  There were no respiratory complications during the case.  Her hemodynamics were mildly labile but were generally on the normotensive side.  Her resuscitation was quite mild, requiring no units of packed red blood cells.  The estimated blood loss was minimal.  She was extubated, had an uneventful recovery room course.
She comes to the intensive care unit for further resuscitation and cardiovascular monitoring purposes.

[end section id="20103"]

